\u20132012\n|               club2 = \u2192 [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]] <small>(on loan)</small>\n|               year2 = 2011\n|               club3 = [[Marylebone Cricket Club]]\n|               year3 = 2002\n|               club4 = [[Northern Districts cricket team|Northern Districts]]\n|               year4 = 2007/08\n|             columns = 4\n|             column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n|            matches1 = 100\n|               runs1 = 7,037\n|            bat avg1 = 40.91\n|           100s/50s1 = 21/27\n|          top score1 = 177\n|         deliveries1 = \u2013\n|            wickets1 = \u2013\n|           bowl avg1 = \u2013\n|            fivefor1 = \u2013\n|             tenfor1 = \u2013\n|       best bowling1 = \u2013\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 121/\u2013\n|             column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n|            matches2 = 127\n|               runs2 = 4,205\n|            bat avg2 = 35.63\n|           100s/50s2 = 6/27\n|          top score2 = 158\n|         deliveries2 = 6\n|            wickets2 = \u2013\n|           bowl avg2 = \u2013\n|            fivefor2 = \u2013\n|             tenfor2 = \u2013\n|       best bowling2 = 0/3\n|  catches/stumpings2 = 57/\u2013\n|             column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n|            matches3 = 241\n|               runs3 = 17,046\n|            bat avg3 = 42.72\n|           100s/50s3 = 46/74\n|          top score3 = 241[[not out|*]]\n|         deliveries3 = 132\n|            wickets3 = 3\n|           bowl avg3 = 47.33\n|            fivefor3 = 0\n|             tenfor3 = 0\n|       best bowling3 = 1/16\n|  catches/stumpings3 = 228/\u2013\n|             column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n|            matches4 = 254\n|               runs4 = 7,631\n|            bat avg4 = 32.75\n|           100s/50s4 = 10/49\n|          top score4 = 163\n|         deliveries4 = 6\n|            wickets4 = 0\n|           bowl avg4 = \u2013\n|            fivefor4 = \u2013\n|             tenfor4 = \u2013\n|       best bowling4 = \u2013\n|  catches/stumpings4 = 90/\u2013\n|                date = 30 October\n|                year = 2017\n|              source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/20387.html Cricinfo\n}}\n\n'''Sir Andrew John Strauss''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (born 2 March 1977) is an English [[cricket]] administrator and former player, currently the Director of Cricket for the [[England and Wales Cricket Board]] (ECB). He played [[county cricket]] for [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]], and captained the [[England cricket team|England]] national team in all formats of the game. A fluent left-handed [[opening batsman]], Strauss favoured scoring off the back foot, mostly playing cut and pull shots. Strauss was also known for his fielding strength at [[Slip (cricket)|slip]] or in the covers. \n\nStrauss made his [[First-class cricket|first-class]] debut in 1998, and his [[One Day International]] (ODI) debut in [[Sri Lanka]] in 2003. He quickly rose to fame on his [[Test cricket|Test match]] debut replacing the injured [[Michael Vaughan]] at [[Lord's]] against [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]] in 2004.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.ecb.co.uk/england/series-tours/ashes-2006/teams/andrew-strauss,11,PP.html England \u2013 News \u2013 ECB]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070307160035/http://www.ecb.co.uk/england/series-tours/ashes-2006/teams/andrew-strauss%2C11%2CPP.html |date=7 March 2007 }}</ref> With scores of 112 and 83 ([[run out]]) in an England victory, and the [[man of the match]] award, he became only the fourth batsman to score a century at Lord's on his debut and was close to becoming the first Englishman to score centuries in both innings of his debut.<ref name=\"cricinfo\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/england/engine/match/64086.html|title=New Zealand in England Test Series \u2013 1st Test England v New Zealand |date=24 May 2004|publisher=CricInfo|accessdate=22 June 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090625194454/http://www.cricinfo.com/england/engine/match/64086.html| archivedate= 25 June 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Strauss again nearly scored two centuries (126 and 94 not out) and was named man of the match in his first overseas Test match, in [[Port Elizabeth]], South Africa, in December 2004.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2004-05/ENG_IN_RSA/SCORECARDS/ENG_RSA_T1_17-21DEC2004.html |title=1st Test: South Africa v England at Port Elizabeth, 17\u201321 December 2004 |publisher=Uk.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> Strauss suffered a drop in form during 2007, and as a result he was left out of the Test squad for England's tour of [[Sri Lanka]], and announced that he was taking a break from cricket.<ref name=rest>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7054967.stm ''Strauss plans break from cricket''] [[BBC News]] retrieved 22 October 2007</ref> After a poor tour for England, Strauss was recalled into the squad for the 2008 tour of New Zealand and subsequently re-established himself in the side with a career-best 177 in the third and final Test of that series, and a further three centuries in 2008.\n\nHaving deputised for Michael Vaughan as [[List of English national cricket captains|England captain]] in 2006, Strauss was appointed on a permanent basis for the [[English cricket team in West Indies in 2008-09|2008\u201309 tour of the West Indies]] following [[Kevin Pietersen]]'s resignation.<ref name=\"cricinfo\">{{cite web|url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/20387.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Players and Officials \u2013 Andrew Strauss |publisher=Content-uk.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> He enjoyed success with three centuries, and retained the captaincy into 2009. Strauss captained the England team to a 2\u20131 victory in the [[2009 Ashes]], scoring a series total of 474 runs, more than any other player on either side,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=4249;type=series |title=The Ashes 2009: most runs |publisher=Stats.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> including 161 in England's first victory in an Ashes Test at Lord's in 75 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345971.html |title=England v Australia at Lord's, 2009 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> He held the record for most catches by an outfield player for England \u2013 going past Botham and Cowdrey at Lords against South Africa in 2012 \u2013 until he was in turn overtaken by Alastair Cook.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/19309373 |title=BBC Sport \u2013 England v South Africa, third Test, day four, Lord's as it happened |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=20 August 2012 |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> He relinquished the Test captaincy and retired from all forms of professional cricket on 29 August 2012, following his 100th test, which concluded a series defeat by South Africa that saw the England Test team lose their number one ranking.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/579864.html | title = Strauss retires from all cricket | author = Andrew McGlashan | publisher = ESPNCricinfo | date = 29 August 2012 | accessdate = 29 August 2012}}</ref> He left the job as the second most successful captain of England in terms of wins, behind only his former opening partner Michael Vaughan.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/19416516 | title = Strauss retirement | work = BBC Sport | date = 30 August 2012 | accessdate = 30 August 2012}}</ref> At the end of his retirement press conference he received an unprecedented round of applause from the assembled media.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/19416516 | title = Agnew on Strauss |work = BBC Sport | date = 30 August 2012 | accessdate = 30 August 2012}}</ref> \n\nHe became the ECB's Director of Cricket in 2015, shortly before the sacking of [[Peter Moores (cricketer)|Peter Moores]].<ref>[http://www.foxsports.com.au/cricket/andrew-strauss-appointed-to-steer-england-crickets-strategy-peter-moores-sacked/story-e6frf3g3-1227348832089 Andrew Strauss appointed to steer England cricket\u2019s strategy, Peter Moores sacked]. AFP. 9 May 2015.</ref> As a result of his services to English Cricket, Strauss was appointed a [[Knights Bachelor|Knight Bachelor]] in [[2019 Prime Minister's Resignation Honours|Theresa May's resignation honours]] on 10 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Resignation Honours 2019 |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/resignation-honours-2019 |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=10 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Education and early life==\nBorn in Johannesburg, South Africa,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/672788 |title=Born in one country, played for another |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=27 April 2018}}</ref> Strauss moved to the UK at the age of six.<ref name=\"tune\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/1632356.stm|title=Strauss calls the tune|last=Brett|first=Oliver|date=1 November 2001|work=BBC News Online|accessdate=13 March 2009}}</ref> He was educated at [[Caldicott School]], a boys' [[Preparatory school (United Kingdom)|prep school]] in Buckinghamshire,<ref name=\"school\">{{cite web|url=http://www.caldicott.com/academic/ce-aamp-scholarship-results/126-academic-results-1989-1990.html |title=Caldicott School Academic Results 1989\u20131990 |publisher=[[Caldicott School]] |accessdate=29 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100521084632/http://www.caldicott.com/academic/ce-aamp-scholarship-results/126-academic-results-1989-1990.html |archivedate=21 May 2010 }}</ref> followed by [[Radley College]], a [[Public school (United Kingdom)|public]] [[boarding school]] for boys in Oxfordshire.<ref name=\"opportunity\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/cricket/andrew-strauss-i-like-to-think-i-will-have-an-opportunity-to-captain-the-england-team-again-416028.html|title=Andrew Strauss: 'I like to think I will have an opportunity to captain the England team again'|last=Viner|first=Brian|date=15 September 2006|work=The Independent |location=UK |accessdate=11 March 2009 }}</ref>\n\nHe studied [[economics]] at the [[University of Durham]], and wrote his [[dissertation]] on [[convex cooperative games|supermodular games]]. In addition to competing for the university he represented the [[Hatfield College, Durham|Hatfield College]] side, where one of his teammates was the future cricket statistician [[Benedict Bermange]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Cricketing Top Scorer from Sky who has never been Stumped|url=https://www.thejc.com/lifestyle/features/the-cricketing-top-scorer-from-sky-who-has-never-been-stumped-1.68224|website=Jewish Chronicle|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref> Strauss also competed for the [[Durham University Rugby Football Club|university rugby club]] as a [[Fly-half]], starting in the 3rd XV and soon moving up to the 2nd XV, but by his final year had dropped this sport to focus more time on cricket.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Andy |title=Andrew Strauss: from scatterbrain to a very English hero |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2011/jan/09/andrew-strauss-ashes-victor |accessdate=15 September 2019 |work=The Observer |date=9 January 2011}}</ref> In a rare distinction, he achieved a full [[palatinate (award)|Palatinate]] for his cricketing activities.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Moyes |first1=Arthur |title=Be The Best You Can Be: A History of Sport in Hatfield College, Durham University |date=2007 |location=Durham |page=103}}</ref> He graduated in 1998 with an [[upper-second class]] [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] degree.<ref name=\"cricinfo\"/>\n\n==Life and career==\nDuring his early career, Strauss spent several years in the cities of Sydney and [[Adelaide]] in Australia, and briefly played [[Grade cricket|first-grade]] cricket alongside Australian bowler [[Brett Lee]].<ref name=\"smh\">{{cite news|title=Strauss a travelling batsman|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/news/strauss-a-travelling-batsman/2006/11/13/1163266484812.html?page=fullpage|newspaper=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=14 November 2006}}</ref> While in Australia he met his future wife, actress Ruth McDonald,<ref name=\"smh\" /> whom he married in October 2003 and lived in [[Marlow, Buckinghamshire|Marlow]], with their sons, Sam (born 4 December 2005) and Luca (14 July 2008).<ref name=\"towels\">{{cite web|url=http://content-ind.cricinfo.com/nzveng/content/story/361104.html|title=Hot water and towels|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=14 July 2008|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=15 July 2008}}</ref> \n\nOn 29 December 2018, Ruth died after a battle with a rare form of lung cancer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/25637744/andrew-strauss-wife-dies-aged-46-cancer-battle |title=Andrew Strauss's wife dies aged 46 after cancer battle |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref> In the wake of Ruth\u2019s death, Andrew reached out to former Ashes adversary [[Glenn McGrath]], who had himself been widowed by cancer after Glenn\u2019s wife Jane \u2013 a native of Paignton, Devon \u2013 had died of breast cancer. Following Jane\u2019s death, Glenn had started the [[McGrath Foundation]] to fight breast cancer and secured the Sydney Test as a partner event, with Jane McGrath Day marked as Day 3 and the stumps, player caps and fan clothes all in pink. Having played in one such Pink Test himself in 2011, Strauss along with the Ruth Strauss Foundation secured Day 2 of the Lord\u2019s Test as a similar partner event ahead of the 2019 Ashes.<ref>[https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27200865/lord-turn-red-ashes-test-support-ruth-strauss-foundation ''Lord's to turn red during Ashes Test in support of Ruth Strauss Foundation'' by Matt Roller] ESPN Cricinfo</ref>\n\nStrauss is President of the Primary Club Juniors, a charity which helps fund blind cricket. In aid of the cause he took part in a blind game, wearing a blindfold and being dismissed on his second ball.<ref name=\"primclub\">{{cite web|url=http://www.primaryclub.org/news/pdf/PrimaryClub_44.pdf|title=Andrew Strauss takes the blind cricket challenge|date=22 May 2006|publisher=[[Primary Club]]|accessdate=11 March 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061211080343/http://www.primaryclub.org/news/pdf/PrimaryClub_44.pdf|archive-date=11 December 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n[[File:Order of the British Empire (Civil) Ribbon.png|thumb|right|85px| '''OBE ribbon''']]\nHe has a variety of nicknames ranging from ''Straussy'', ''[[Levi Strauss|Levi]]'' and ''[[Johann Strauss II|Johann]]'', to the more obscure ''[[Charles Nall-Cain, 3rd Baron Brocket|Lord Brocket]]'', ''Mareman'', ''The General'', ''Jazzer'', ''Muppet'' and ''Mr Potato Head''.<ref name=\"cricinfo\"/><ref name=\"mccc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.middlesexccc.com/player-profile.asp?PlayerID=20 |title=Middlesex County Cricket Club Profile |publisher=[[Middlesex County Cricket Club]] |accessdate=9 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401171011/http://www.middlesexccc.com/player-profile.asp?PlayerID=20 |archivedate=1 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAlready [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE), Strauss was promoted to [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[2011 Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59808 |date=11 June 2011 |page=12 |supp=y}}</ref> His alma mater, Durham University, conferred the [[honorary doctorate]] of [[Doctor of Civil Law|DCL]] upon him in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/ceremonies/congregation/honorary/speeches/|title=Ceremonies Unit : Orations for Honorary Awards \u2013 Durham University|website=Dur.ac.uk|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nStrauss has written several books on his professional career, ''Coming Into Play: My Life in Test Cricket'' (2006),<ref name=\"Strauss2006\">{{cite book|author=Andrew Strauss|title=Andrew Strauss:Coming Into Play: My Life in Test Cricket|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yRqXAQAACAAJ|year=2006|publisher=Hodder & Stoughton|isbn=978-0-340-84066-5}}</ref> ''Testing Times: In Pursuit of the Ashes'' (2010, with [[Scyld Berry]]),<ref name=\"StraussBerry2010\">{{cite book|author1=Andrew Strauss|author2=Scyld Berry|title=Testing Times: In Pursuit of the Ashes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=52GQAAAACAAJ|year=2010|publisher=Hodder General Publishing Division|isbn=978-0-340-84070-2}}</ref> ''Winning the Ashes Down Under: The Captains Story'' (2011),<ref name=\"Strauss2011\">{{cite book|author=Andrew Strauss|title=Andrew Strauss: Winning the Ashes Down Under: Winning the Ashes Down Under|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u2egoMSslIkC|date=4 August 2011|publisher=Hodder & Stoughton|isbn=978-1-4447-3622-9}}</ref> and an autobiography, ''Driving Ambition'', in 2014.<ref name=\"Strauss2014\">{{cite book|author=Andrew Strauss|title=Andrew Strauss \u2013  Driving Ambition: My Autobiography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2GHeAAAACAAJ|date=9 October 2014|publisher=Hodder General Publishing Division|isbn=978-0-340-89789-8}}</ref>\n\nPolitically, Strauss is a Conservative, raising money for them in a charity auction. [[David Cameron]] tried to persuade Strauss to become an MP in 2013, but Strauss turned down the offer.<ref>Glaze, Ben (11 October 2015) [https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/blundering-david-cameron-tried-persuade-6614056 Blundering David Cameron 'tried to persuade Ashes hero Andrew Strauss to become Tory MP']. Mirror.co.uk . Retrieved on 24 May 2018.</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Ross, Tim |title=Why the Tories Won: The Inside Story of the 2015 Election |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zze5CgAAQBAJ&pg=PT15 |date=12 October 2015 |publisher=Biteback Publishing |isbn=978-1-78590-007-5 |pages=15\u2013}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic career===\nHaving played for the [[Durham UCCE|Durham University]] cricket team and the [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]] second XI since 1996, Strauss made his Middlesex first XI debut in 1998, scoring 83 in his maiden [[first-class cricket|first-class]] innings.<ref>{{cite web |url-access=subscription  |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/66/66398.html |title=Hampshire v Middlesex, 1998 |publisher=Cricketarchive.com |date=3 September 1998 |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> Despite this, he made a quiet start: he averaged 24 and 30.5 in his first two first-class seasons,<ref name=\"season avs\">{{cite web |url-access=subscription  |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/7/7005/f_Batting_by_Season.html |title=Andrew Strauss batting averages by season |publisher=Cricketarchive.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> and he did not make his maiden first-class century until an innings of 111 not out two years after his debut.<ref>{{cite web |url-access=subscription  |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/69/69686.html |title=Middlesex v Northamptonshire, 2000 |publisher=Cricketarchive.com |date=6 May 2000 |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> Thereafter, Strauss's stock rose quickly: his returns in 2001, 2002 and 2003 were 1211 runs at an average of 45, 1202 at 48 and 1529 at 51.<ref name=\"season avs\"/> He was appointed captain of [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]] in 2002, following the retirement of [[Angus Fraser]], and retained the post until the end of the 2004 season.<ref name=\"caprof\">{{cite web |url-access=subscription  |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/7/7005/7005.html|title=Cricket Archive profile|publisher=Cricket Archive|accessdate=9 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090228195022/http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/7/7005/7005.html| archivedate= 28 February 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> In late August 2011, Strauss hit his highest first-class score of 241 not out against [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]], beating his previous best of 177.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = County Championship Division Two, Middlesex v Leicestershire at Lord's, Aug&nbsp;30 \u2013 Sep 2, 2011\n| url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/engine/current/match/492219.html\n| publisher = ESPN Cricinfo\n| accessdate =31 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nStrauss is a Committee Member of [[Marylebone Cricket Club]].\n\n===International career===\n\n====Debut year (2003\u201304)====\nStrauss's first taste of international cricket came as part of England's tour of the sub-continent,<ref name=\"b03squad\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/ENG_IN_BDESH/ENG_IN_BDESH_OCT-NOV2003_ENG-SQUAD.html|title=England in Bangladesh, Oct \u2013 Nov 2003 squads|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> but he would only fulfil the role of the [[Cricket terminology#T|twelfth man]]; despite considering himself better in the long form of the game, Strauss was surprised to be selected for the One Day squad.<ref name=\"odicall\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/132404.html|title=Strauss \u2013 ' I was expecting a Test call-up, not a one-day one'|last=Auld|first=Freddie|date=6 November 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> Although he was not selected for the main team, Strauss did make an appearance in a tour match, starring with 51 in an opening partnership of 146 in a slow, but fluent innings.<ref name=\"b04tour\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/132381.html|title=Solanki and Strauss star in England stroll|last=Randall|first=Nicholas|date=5 November 2003|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> As England moved straight from Bangladesh to Sri Lanka, Strauss continued to put pressure on England opener [[Vikram Solanki]] in a tour match top scoring with 83, juxtaposed with Solanki's five ball duck<ref name=\"solpress\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/131887.html|title=Strauss puts the pressure on Solanki|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=15 November 2003|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> and was rewarded with his England debut in a disastrous ten-wicket defeat where he was caught and bowled by fellow debutant [[Dinusha Fernando]]<ref name=\"sri103o\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64846.html|title=1st ODI: Sri Lanka v England at Dambulla, Nov&nbsp;18, 2003|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> and was subsequently omitted for the rest of the tour.\n\nStrauss was given another chance in the tour of the West Indies, even being called up to the Test squad owing to the injury of [[Mark Butcher]].<ref name=\"testcallup\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/139773.html|title=Strauss called up to England Test squad|date=5 March 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> Still he was only given a chance in the ODI team, but he made an impact even at his un-native number three position top scoring with 29 in a tense England win.<ref name=\"wind104o\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64886.html|title=1st ODI: West Indies v England at Georgetown, April&nbsp;18, 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> Despite this he was omitted, after the second abandoned match, until the fifth ODI where he contributed only 10<ref name=\"wind504o\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64893.html|title=5th ODI: West Indies v England at Gros Islet, May&nbsp;1, 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> but made up for it joint top scoring with skipper [[Michael Vaughan]] and putting on a good start in an ultimately losing match, making a great first international catch.<ref name=\"wind604o\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/140614.html|title=West Indies cruise to victory|last=Auld|first=Freddie|date=2 May 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> He also contributed 66 to help win the final match, drawing the series.<ref name=\"wind704o\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64895.html|title=7th ODI: West Indies v England at Bridgetown, May&nbsp;5, 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090327141001/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64895.html| archivedate= 27 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lord's honours board (cropped).jpg|left|thumb|Strauss was added to the [[Lord's Honours Boards|Lord's honours board]] for scoring a century on his Test debut]]\nStrauss returned home to start the 2004 English season but was chosen to make his Test debut for England after Vaughan sustained a knee injury in the [[cricket nets|nets]].<ref name=\"nz105wisden\">{{cite web|url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/231698.html|title=First Test match England v New Zealand|last=Walters|first=Mike|work=[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=9 March 2009}}</ref> The initial plan was to promote [[Mark Butcher]] to the vacant [[opening batsman]] position and include [[Paul Collingwood]] in the [[middle order]]. Butcher declined to move up the order and batted third, meaning Strauss was asked to open the batting and Collingwood missed out on a place in the side.<ref name=\"braced\">{{cite web|url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/141052.html|title=England braced for loss of Vaughan|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=19 May 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=9 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"trescolead\">{{cite web|url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/141053.html|title=Trescothick to lead England|date=19 May 2004|work=[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=9 March 2009}}</ref> Vaughan's injury turned out to be fortunate for Strauss who, in his first Test innings, top scored with 112 and contributed 82 in the second innings<ref name=\"nz104\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64086.html|title=1st Test: England v New Zealand at Lord's, May&nbsp;20\u201324, 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090321085415/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64086.html| archivedate= 21 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> before being run out, with [[Nasser Hussain]] taking responsibility for the dismissal.<ref name=\"hussainvictory\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/3741789.stm|title=Hussain seals victory|date=24 May 2004|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=9 March 2009}}</ref> This put Strauss on a series of exclusive lists including being the second English player to score a century on his debut at Lord's, third opener to score a hundred on debut,<ref name=\"debut100\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/cricket/century-on-test-debut-gives-strauss-his-place-in-history-564260.html|title=Century on Test debut gives Strauss his place in history|last=Fraser|first=Angus|date=22 May 2004|work=The Independent |location=UK |accessdate=12 March 2009 }}</ref> the fifteenth English player to score a century on his debut, the first since [[Graham Thorpe]] in 1993 and only the fourth English player to score a century and half century on his debut.<ref name=\"boil\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/4774428.stm|title=Cook comes to boil|last=Brown|first=Gavin|date=6 March 2006|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=28 February 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"buzzing\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/2333215/Still-buzzing-after-a-dream-debut.html|title=Still buzzing after a dream debut|last=Cook|first=Alastair|date=7 March 2006|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK |accessdate=3 March 2009 }}</ref> Strauss also made the first dismissal of the Test, catching [[Stephen Fleming]] off [[Simon Jones (cricketer)|Simon Jones]] and was awarded [[Man of The Match]] for his efforts.<ref name=\"nz104\"/> The performance by Strauss excelled his role as a filler for Vaughan, leading to Hussain retiring from cricket allowing for Vaughan to move down the order and Strauss retaining the role of opener opposite [[Marcus Trescothick]].<ref name=\"hussainfuture\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/3744149.stm|title=Hussain ponders future|date=24 May 2004|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> Strauss' form declined over the series, with one half century in the second Test<ref name=\"nz204\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64087.html|title=2nd Test: England v New Zealand at Leeds, July&nbsp;3\u20137, 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090323221332/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64087.html| archivedate= 23 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> and his first Test duck along with a six in the third Test.<ref name=\"nz304\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64088.html|title=3rd Test: England v New Zealand at Nottingham, Jun&nbsp;10\u201313 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090319080909/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64088.html| archivedate= 19 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn the ensuing [[NatWest Series|NatWest tri-series]] that bridged the two tours, England won only one match, where Strauss guided them home with an [[not out|unbeaten]] 44,<ref name=\"win504o\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/66306.html|title=5th Match: England v West Indies at Leeds, Jul&nbsp;1, 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> even losing against the West Indies after a century-each partnership of 226 with [[Andrew Flintoff]] at Lord's with Strauss recording his first One Day century with an exact 100.<ref name=\"wind804o\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/66309.html|title=8th Match: England v West Indies at Lord's, July&nbsp;6, 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> Strauss continued to make Lord's a talisman as he returned for the opening Test of the series against West Indies with another century opposite [[Robert Key (cricketer)|Robert Key's]] 221 in a winning effort; the two also set the record for highest second wicket partnership against the West Indies.<ref name=\"wind104home\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64093.html|title=1st Test: England v West Indies at Lord's, Jul&nbsp;22\u201326 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090307015355/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64093.html| archivedate= 7 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> In the third Test at [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground|Old Trafford]] where [[Brian Lara]] scored his ten thousandth run, Strauss faltered after five hours at the crease falling just short of another century at 90.<ref name=\"wind304home\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64095.html|title=3rd Test: England v West Indies at Manchester, Aug&nbsp;12\u201316 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090320224727/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64095.html| archivedate= 20 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> In the final part of a packed 2004 season, Strauss guided England to victory with 44 not out against India in the [[NatWest Series#NatWest Challenge|NatWest Challenge]] opening One Day match<ref name=\"ind104\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/65032.html|title=1st Match: England v India at Nottingham, Sep&nbsp;1 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090321090338/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/65032.html| archivedate= 21 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> but only scored 2 a piece in the following two matches.<ref name=\"odianalysis\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/player/20387.html?class=2;template=results;type=allround;view=match|title=One Day Internationals analysis|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> Then, in the [[2004 ICC Champions Trophy]] at home Strauss contributed towards a win against [[Zimbabwean cricket team|Zimbabwe]]<ref name=\"zim104\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/66196.html|title=1st Match: England v Zimbabwe at Birmingham, Sep&nbsp;10\u201311 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> and then starred in the semi-final against old enemies [[Australian cricket team|Australia]] with 52 not out from 42.<ref name=\"aus104\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/66208.html|title=1st semi-final: England v Australian at Birmingham, Sep&nbsp;21 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> However, along with the rest of the team aside from Trescothick he failed to muster a decent total in the final allowing West Indies to take the trophy.<ref name=\"finalwind04\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/66210.html|title=Final: England v West Indies at The Oval, Sep&nbsp;25 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Road to The Ashes (2004\u201305)====\n[[File:Andrew Strauss Lords.jpg|thumb|Strauss batting against Bangladesh at [[Lord's]]]]\n\nThe runners-up in the Champions Trophy took October off before beginning a tour of Africa in November. Their first port of call was Zimbabwe, visiting for the first time since the [[2003 Cricket World Cup#Zimbabwe's political situation|2003 World Cup political concerns]] and despite being minnows Strauss could not muster even a half century in the 4\u20130 series win.<ref name=\"odianalysis\"/> In the final match, Strauss was called on to bowl a single over, conceding three runs.<ref name=\"zim404\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64913.html|title=4th ODI: Zimbabwe v England at Bulawayo, Dec&nbsp;5 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> England then moved to Strauss' native South Africa for a five Test series taking them into the new year. His homecoming was an explosive one as he caught captain [[Graeme Smith]] off the second ball and went on to score his first away century with 126 before scoring over half of the team's second innings score as he steered them towards victory, again falling short of twin hundreds with 94 not out; still he became only the seventh Test player to record a century on his home and away debut.<ref name=\"homeaway\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/4108057.stm|title=Strauss waltzes into record books|last=Brett|first=Oliver|date=18 December 2004|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"sa104\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64116.html|title=1st Test: South Africa v England at Port Elizabeth, Dec&nbsp;17\u201321 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090320224731/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64116.html| archivedate= 20 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Despite missing out on this accolade he did record back to back centuries, in the Boxing Day Test he top scored in the first innings with only 25 as it seemed England were set for defeat, Strauss and Trescothick bolstered the side with an opening partnership stand of 273, top scoring with 136 to help England push for victory though it would end in a draw.<ref name=\"sa204\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64117.html|title=2nd Test: South Africa v England at Durban, 26\u201330 2004|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090310030013/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64117.html| archivedate= 10 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> In the losing, third Test Strauss not only top scored in the first innings with 45, he also became the fourth fastest Englishman to reach 1,000 Test runs in 19 innings.<ref name=\"thousand\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/4143257.stm|title=South Africa rock England batsmen|date=3 January 2005|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=13 March 2009}}</ref> After his third century of the tour in the fourth Test that helped secure the decisive victory<ref name=\"sa405\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64119.html|title=4th Test: South Africa v England at Johannesburg, Jan&nbsp;13\u201317 2005|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090313012840/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64119.html| archivedate= 13 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Strauss ended with a pair of ducks in the fourth and fifth Test preventing England from extending the lead to 3\u20131.<ref name=\"sa405\"/><ref name=\"sa505\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64120.html|title=5th Test: South Africa v England at Centurion, Jan&nbsp;21\u201325 2005|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090319080914/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/64120.html| archivedate= 19 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Despite the two zeroes, Strauss dominated the batsmen of the series making 656 runs over the five matches at an average of 72.88<ref name=\"sa05avg\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2004-05/ENG_IN_RSA/STATS/ENG_IN_RSA_DEC2004-FEB2005_TEST_AVS.html|title=England in South Africa, 2004\u201305 Test Series Averages|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=13 March 2009}}</ref> and earned his first Man of The Series award. In the losing One Day series that followed Strauss failed to impress with the bat, never making more than 35.<ref name=\"odianalysis\"/> Nevertheless, his Test success drew the plaudits of, among others, future Australian rival [[Justin Langer]].<ref name=\"substance\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/4188581.stm|title=Strauss adds substance to style|last=Langer|first=Justin|date=25 January 2005|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nAfter the tour, England returned home to play Bangladesh with Strauss's home ground of Lord's only helping him towards a half century in the one innings they played.<ref name=\"ban105\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/209929.html|title=1st Test: England v Bangladesh at Lord's, May&nbsp;26\u201328, 2005|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> In the following [[NatWest Series]] against Bangladesh and Australia, England built on their momentum going into the Ashes series by making their way to the top of the group and into the final.<ref name=\"nw5\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/statistics/3679990.stm|title=NatWest Series 2005|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=13 March 2009 | date=2 July 2005}}</ref> Individually, Strauss posted 82* and 98 in the first and last matches against Bangladesh,<ref name=\"odianalysis\"/> with a One Day high score of 152 from 128 balls in the middle match<ref name=\"ban405\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/211579.html|title=4th Match: England v Bangladesh at Nottingham, Jun&nbsp;21 2005|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=13 March 2009}}</ref> but fared less well against Australia, never scoring more than 25 and only managing 2 in the tied final at Lord's.<ref name=\"odianalysis\"/> Strauss was significantly shuffled down the order in England's inaugural [[Twenty20 International]] against Australia and made 18 in their 100 run win<ref name=\"aus05t20\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005/AUS_IN_ENG/SCORECARDS/AUS_ENG_TWENTY-20-I_13JUN2005.html|title=Twenty20 International: England v Australia at Southampton, Jun&nbsp;13 2005|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=13 March 2009}}</ref> and in the losing NatWest Challenge scored favourably, but not notable, with two scores near 50.<ref name=\"odianalysis\"/>\n\n====The Ashes (2005)====\n[[File:Strauss dismissal.jpg|thumb|Strauss is caught by [[Michael Clarke (cricketer)|Michael Clarke]] chasing 129 to win the fourth Test]]\nGoing into the [[2005 Ashes series]] having not won since the 1980s but with an unbeaten series record going back six series it was a highly anticipated series with Australian captain [[Ricky Ponting]] predicting it to be the closest Ashes since England's last win.<ref name=\"pontingwary\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/4393065.stm|title=Ponting wary of improved England|date=30 March 2005|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=13 March 2009}}</ref> Seemingly the pressure affected Strauss even at Lord's, along with the rest of the team, as he contributed 2 to their 155 and a slightly more impressive 37 to their 180 in a losing first Test, though Strauss did catch Ponting in the first innings.<ref name=\"aus105\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/213856.html|title=1st Test: England v Australia at Lord's, Jul&nbsp;21\u201324 2005|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=13 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090321014319/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/213856.html| archivedate= 21 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> The second Test proved to be a much more dramatic affair and Strauss improved somewhat on his showing at Lord's with an opening stand of 112 opposite Trescothick, falling two short of a half century to the spin of [[Shane Warne]].<ref name=\"aus205\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/215010.html|title=2nd Test: England v Australia at Birmingham, Aug&nbsp;4\u20137 2005|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=13 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090310175445/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/215010.html| archivedate= 10 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> While this healthy platform pushed England towards a 99 run lead in the first innings, it was Strauss' paltry second innings of six which garnered more attention:<ref name=\"testoftime\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/wisdencricketer/content/story/220056.html|title=Standing the Test of time|last=Haigh|first=Gideon|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=13 March 2009}}</ref> four deliveries before the end of play on day two a Warne legbreak spun prodigiously from the rough across Strauss' body to knock down leg stump.<ref name=\"warnespin\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2005/aug/06/ashes2005.ashes8|title=England hold sway but still fear the genius of Warne|last=Selvey|first=Mike|date=6 August 2005|work=The Guardian |location=UK |accessdate=13 March 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"warnespin2\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/4747865.stm|title=England take control at Edgebaston|date=5 August 2005|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=13 March 2009}}</ref> Those six runs are arguably crucial though, as England's winning margin was simply two runs.<ref name=\"aus205\"/> The number six would follow him into the next Test at Old Trafford, making way for Vaughan to bat the first century of the series. Strauss followed in his captain's footsteps in the second innings adding 106 of his own to help set a target of 371 for the Australians who managed to stave off losing their final wicket to secure a draw and maintain a 1\u20131 series score.<ref name=\"aus305\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/215686.html|title=3rd Test: England v Australia at Manchester, Aug&nbsp;11\u201315 2005|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=13 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090530005637/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/215686.html| archivedate=30 May 2009| url-status= live}}</ref>\n[[File:England Cricket Celebrations.jpg|left|thumb|England celebrate in [[Trafalgar Square]] after winning the Ashes]]\nIn the fourth Test Strauss helped England to a fine start with a century first wicket partnership, contributing 35 himself and helping restrict Australia to 218 with two catches, specifically fast striker [[Adam Gilchrist]] in an exceedingly wide catch at slip which was called \"the abiding image of the Summer\".<ref name=\"supercatch\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/ci/content/image/222570.html|title=The abiding image of the summer|last=Eager|first=Patrick|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=18 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090307113307/http://content.cricinfo.com/ci/content/image/222570.html| archivedate= 7 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> After enforcing the [[follow-on]] England were set 129 and the batsmen started falling under pressure, with Strauss lasting until the third wicket down and posting one of four scores within the twenties to help win the Test and take the series lead.<ref name=\"aus405\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/216994.html|title=4th Test: England v Australia at Nottingham, Aug&nbsp;25\u201328 2005|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=13 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090321014324/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/216994.html| archivedate= 21 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> With only a draw required in the final Test to take home the Ashes, Strauss showed a winning attitude batting for almost all of the first day, with seven partnerships, to put on 129<ref name=\"aus505\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/218383.html|title=5th Test: England v Australia at The Oval, Sep&nbsp;8\u201312 2005|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=13 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090321014329/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/218383.html| archivedate= 21 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> and secure another Ashes hundred and make himself the only batsmen on either team to record two centuries in the series.<ref name=\"ashes05avg\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005/AUS_IN_ENG/STATS/AUS_IN_ENG_JUN-SEP2005_TEST_AVS.html|title=Australia in England, 2005 Test Series Averages|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=13 March 2009}}</ref> Once again Strauss made a notable catch in the field helping to dismiss captain Ponting again,<ref name=\"aus505\"/> Australia's second best batsman in the series,<ref name=\"ashes05avg\"/> as well as sending fast bowler [[Glenn McGrath]] back to the pavilion for a duck. Unfortunately Strauss could not keep up his sterling performance as England were put back into bat with just over a day left in the series he fell to Warne again, caught by [[Simon Katich]], for a single run. Regardless, the maiden Test century of fellow South African-born England player [[Kevin Pietersen]] stalled Australia from taking victory and England won the series 2\u20131 to take home the Ashes for the first time in 18 years.<ref name=\"aus505\"/>\n\nIn a series arguably dominated more by bowling than batting, Strauss notched up an average of 39.30 and while he was only the fourth highest scoring batsmen for England with 393, only one Australian, Justin Langer, scored more runs than him and by only one run; Strauss was also the only player to score two centuries and made six catches, the second highest fielder behind [[Ian Bell]] for England.<ref name=\"ashes05avg\"/> While captain Michael Vaughan and coach [[Duncan Fletcher]] were awarded [[Order of the British Empire|OBEs]], the rest of the team, Strauss included, were given MBEs in the New Years Honours list.<ref name=\"mbeox\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/oxfordshire/4571600.stm|title=Writer tops Oxfordshire honours|date=31 December 2005|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=13 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"mbe\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/front_page/4570808.stm|title=Honours for Ashes and 2012 heroes|date=31 December 2005|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=13 March 2009}}</ref> (Strauss subsequently was awarded the OBE in the 2011 [[Birthday Honours]] list.<ref name=\"obe\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/front_page/13726861.stm|title=Andrew Strauss and Alastair Cook lead Birthday Honours list|date=10 June 2011|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=11 June 2011}}</ref>)\n\n====Facing Asian teams and early captaincy (2005\u201306)====\n\nIn the Winter months that followed, [[English cricket team in Pakistan in 2005\u201306|England toured Pakistan]] following their Ashes success looking to extend their unbeaten streak of six Test series (with only two lost Tests) since 2004.<ref name=\"engtestseries\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/england/engine/records/team/series_results.html?class=1;id=1;type=team|title=Series results England \u2013 Test matches|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref> Strauss started the tour unnervingly, with warm up scores of two fives and a six,<ref name=\"paktour205\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/224264.html|title=Tour match: Pakistan A v England XI at Lahore, Nov&nbsp;6\u20138 2005|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"paktour105\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/ci/content/match/223689.html|title=Tour match: Patron's XI v England XI at Rawalpindi, Oct&nbsp;31 \u2013 Nov&nbsp;2 2005|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref> mustering 56 in the final warm up innings.<ref name=\"paktour205\"/> Despite acknowledging his batting problems,<ref name=\"pakbatcris\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/4412026.stm|title=Strauss dismisses batting crisis|date=6 November 2005|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref> Strauss' performance never recovered as he scored only 44 runs in the first two Test matches, losing the first and drawing the second, at an average of 11<ref name=\"pak05avg\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/pakveng/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=2649;team=1;type=series|title=Batting and bowling averages England in Pakistan Test Series, 2005/06 \u2013 England|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref> before he departed Pakistan to attend the birth of his first child, missing England's final loss.<ref name=\"firstchild\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/4470434.stm|title=England unlikely to opt for Cook|date=25 November 2005|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref> Strauss returned for the One Day series but showed little improvement with only five runs in the tour match,<ref name=\"paktour305\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/ci/content/match/228814.html|title=Tour match: Pakistan A v England XI Lahore 7&nbsp;Dec 2005 |publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref> but found more success shuffled down to third man, top scoring 94 to help England win the first match.<ref name=\"pak105o\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/226352.html|title=1st ODI: Pakistan v England at Lahore, Dec&nbsp;10 2005|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref> He also scored 26 runs in the low scoring, final match which England also won<ref name=\"pak5050\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/226356.html|title=5th ODI: Pakistan v England at Rawalpindi, Dec&nbsp;21 2005|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref> but in between picked up a pair of ducks.<ref name=\"pak05avgodi\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=2656;team=1;type=series|title=Batting and bowling averages England in Pakistan ODI Series, 2005/06 \u2013 England|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe other side of Christmas, [[English cricket team in India in 2005\u201306|England went to India in March]] and after Trescothick absented himself owing to stress-related illness, Strauss found himself opening England's batting with 21-year-old debutante [[Alastair Cook]]. Cook repeated Strauss' debut theatrics, scoring a half and full century, overshadowing Strauss's 28 and 46 in the drawn match.<ref name=\"ind105\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/239025.html|title=1st Test: India v England at Nagpur, Mar1-5 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=16 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090315081809/http://content.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/239025.html| archivedate= 15 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Without Cook opposite him in the third Test, Strauss shone once again with 128 in a winning effort to level the series.<ref name=\"ind306\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/238187.html|title=3rd Test: India v England at Mumbai, Mar&nbsp;18\u201322 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=16 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090315083712/http://content.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/238187.html| archivedate= 15 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> In the following One Day matches England would have been lucky to manage a draw, suffering four straight losses under replacement captain [[Andrew Flintoff]] since Vaughan's knee-injury had prevented him from touring.<ref name=\"vaughan06inj\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/4757606.stm|title=Vaughan set to miss rest of tour|date=2 March 2006|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=17 March 2009}}</ref> Strauss's only double digit score was 61 in the second match<ref name=\"odianalysis\"/> but with Flintoff requiring a break from deputising, Strauss was handed the captaincy for the fifth match which ultimately was abandoned, leading to crowd violence in [[Guwahati]].<ref name=\"ind506o\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/4890448.stm|title=Violence follows England wash-out|date=9 April 2006|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=17 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090414105512/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/4890448.stm| archivedate= 14 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> With Flintoff remaining the twelfth man for the following ODI,<ref name=\"ind605review\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/4901904.stm|title=Strauss leads way in England win|date=12 April 2006|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=17 March 2009}}</ref> Strauss guided England to victory after putting India to bat, with a hundred partnership with [[Ian Bell]] totalling 74 before cramp forced him to retire.<ref name=\"ind606o\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/238193.html|title=6th ODI: India v England at Jamshedpur, 12&nbsp;Apr 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=17 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090501015259/http://content.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/238193.html| archivedate= 1 May 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> The emphatic, eight over victory was to be England's only One Day success on the tour as the final match saw India chase the runs victoriously with only five balls remaining with Strauss offering only 25.<ref name=\"ind706o\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/238194.html|title=7th ODI: India v England at Indore, 15&nbsp;Apr 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=17 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nAs England returned home weary from an entire Winter without a series victory after the euphoria of the previous two years, they completed a [[Indian subcontinent|subcontinental]] triumvirate when [[Sri Lankan cricket team in England in 2006|Sri Lanka arrived]] to prove that Asian dominance was not particular to the Indian subcontinent. With the captaincy crown returned to Flintoff, Strauss could focus solely on his batting prowess at the ground that made him famous. Opening once again with Trescothick, Strauss fell two short of a half century to the bowling of [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] at the stroke of lunch, allowing Cook to walk out to the wicket afterwards with company. Strauss went on to take the final wicket of Sri Lanka's first innings, [[Nuwan Kulasekara]], catching him off Flintoff to allow England to enforce the follow-on which they could not capitalise on, forcing a draw.<ref name=\"sri106\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225264.html|title=1st Test: England v Sri Lanka, 11\u201315&nbsp;May 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=17 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090302101508/http://content-www.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225264.html| archivedate= 2 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> In the second Test, England took the lead with a victory after Strauss scored the second highest runs in both English innings, being controversially caught for 16 in the second off his pads.<ref name=\"sri206r\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/5025004.stm|title=England seal second Test triumph|date=28 May 2006|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=28 February 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"sri206\">{{cite web|url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/225265.html|title=2nd Test: England v Sri Lanka at Birmingham, May&nbsp;25\u201328, 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=28 February 2009}}</ref> He recorded another half century in the third Test, though it was not enough to stave off a 134 run defeat.<ref name=\"sri305\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225266.html|title=3rd Test: England v Sri Lanka at Nottingham, Jun&nbsp;2\u20135 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=17 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090319223608/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225266.html| archivedate= 19 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Once again he was offered the captaincy for the short form game, leading England in a tense, two run loss to Sri Lanka where he put on an opening partnership with Trescothick for 59.<ref name=\"sriti107\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225271.html|title=Only T20I: England v Sri Lanka at Southampton, Jun&nbsp;16 2007|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=18 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090407054748/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225271.html| archivedate= 7 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Under Strauss' captaincy England endured a five match whitewash where Strauss failed to muster even fifty<ref name=\"sri06avgodi\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/engvsl/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=2640;team=1;type=series|title=Batting and bowling averages NatWest Series [Sri Lanka in England], 2006 \u2013 England|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=18 March 2009}}</ref> though it was acknowledged that the team, particularly the bowling side, were under strength.<ref name=\"sri06marks\">{{cite web|url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvsl/content/story/252123.html|title=From bad to hopeless|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=2 July 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=27 February 2008}}</ref>\n\nDespite the One Day 'whitewash', Strauss was given faith and made the official captain, rather than a stand in, for [[Pakistani cricket team in England in 2006|Pakistan's Summer tour]] as England embarked on their busy international schedule leading up to the Ashes and the World Cup.<ref name=\"captain06\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/252362.html|title=Strauss named as England captain|date=4 July 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=19 March 2009}}</ref> Given the Test captaincy, his first match was at his favourite ground Lord's where he recorded another century, 128 this time, in the second innings<ref name=\"pak106\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225255.html|title=1st Test: England v Pakistan at Lord's, Jul&nbsp;13\u201317 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=19 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090318092645/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225255.html| archivedate= 18 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> but came under criticism for allowing his bowlers only 80 overs for victory, which they did not achieve.<ref name=\"pak106bbc\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/5185824.stm|title=Inzamam helps earn Pakistan draw|date=17 July 2006|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=19 March 2009}}</ref> He turned things round drastically in the second Test with tight fielding that restricted Pakistan to under 250 in both innings while contributing 42 to England's high strike rate 461, allowing an emphatic innings victory in just three days.<ref name=\"pak206\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225256.html|title=2nd Test: England v Pakistan at Manchester, Jul&nbsp;27\u201329 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=19 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090316094805/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225256.html| archivedate= 16 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Though the third Test was not quite as emphatic, England still won the Test after restricting the second innings, not allowing any centuries like in the other three innings and scoring one himself, 116, to take an unassailable lead in his first Test series as captain.<ref name=\"pak306\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225257.html|title=3rd Test: England v Pakistan at Leeds, Aug&nbsp;4\u20138 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=19 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090318135451/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225257.html| archivedate= 18 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Strauss' first Test series as skipper ended in an amount of controversy at The Oval in what some commentators have referred to as [[Ball tampering#Ball tampering controversy in August 2006|Ovalgate]] when, during their second innings, umpires [[Darrell Hair]] and [[Billy Doctrove]] inspected the ball and decided that it had been tampered with. Insulted by the allegation, the Pakistan team protested by not taking to the field after the tea break leading the umpires to declare the match forfeited. Pakistan later tried to take to the field but the umpires upheld their decision.<ref name=\"ovalgate\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/5268886.stm|title=Lengthy talks fail to save Test|date=20 August 2006|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=19 March 2009}}</ref> Two years later the decision was changed to a draw after a petition from Pakistan,<ref name=\"ovalchange\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/7485935.stm|title=Oval Test result changed to a draw|date=3 June 2008|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=19 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090205165059/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/7485935.stm| archivedate= 5 February 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> but in February 2009 the original decision was reinstated amidst criticism of the precedent such historicism would set.<ref name=\"ovaluturn\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/7863464.stm|title=Result U-turn for 2006 Oval Test|date=1 February 2009|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=19 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090204100322/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/7863464.stm| archivedate= 4 February 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> The series thus ended 3\u20130 to England, with Strauss being awarded Player of The Series<ref name=\"pak406\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225258.html|title=4th Test: England v Pakistan at The Oval, Aug&nbsp;17\u201321 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=19 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090321085335/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225258.html| archivedate= 21 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> due to being the top of England's run scorers, behind only to [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricketer, born 1974)|Mohammed Yousuf]] on either side.<ref name=\"pak06avgt\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=2641;type=series|title=Most runs Pakistan in England Test Series, 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=19 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nStrauss continues his captaincy with the limited overs team. He performed less well in the one-off Twenty20 International, falling for a duck while Pakistan soared to victory with two overs to spare<ref name=\"pakti06\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225263.html|title=Only T20I: England v Pakistan at Bristol, Aug&nbsp;28 2006|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=19 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090331081338/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225263.html| archivedate= 31 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> and his luck remained the same as the One Day series began. After two low scores<ref name=\"odianalysis\"/> he scored 50 in the third match though the team would still lose,<ref name=\"pak305odi\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225247.html|title=3rd Match: England v Pakistan at Southampton, Sep&nbsp;5 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=19 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090420133248/http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225247.html| archivedate= 20 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> however his 78 in the fourth match propped up an eight wicket win<ref name=\"pak406o\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225248.html|title=4th Match: England v Pakistan at Nottingham, Sep&nbsp;8 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=19 March 2009}}</ref> and a top score of 35 earned England a 2\u20132 draw in the series.<ref name=\"pak506o\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/225249.html|title=5th Match: England v Pakistan at Birmingham, Sep&nbsp;10 2006|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=19 March 2009}}</ref> The following month England returned to the sub-continent for the [[2006 ICC Champions Trophy|Champions Trophy in India]]. Strauss scored two half centuries in three matches<ref name=\"odianalysis\"/> but the team as a whole played disastrously with only one victory over the West Indies.<ref name=\"cham06\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/iccct2006/engine/series/232694.html?view=pointstable|title=ICC Champions Trophy Group Tables, 2006/07|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=19 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Decline in form (2006\u201307)====\nAfter the Champions Trophy the captaincy reverted to Andrew Flintoff as soon as he was cleared as being match fit.<ref name=\"flincapt\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/5333960.stm|title=Flintoff named skipper for Ashes|date=12 September 2006|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=19 March 2009}}</ref> Strauss started the tour badly, scoring only 71 runs from the first four innings along with a generally terrible display from England. After losing the first two Tests, questions were asked about a divided dressing room owing to the captaincy changing hands so frequently between Strauss and Flintoff but Strauss played down these accusations.<ref name=\"ashescpt\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6166315.stm|title=Strauss denies row over captaincy|date=10 December 2006|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=20 March 2009}}</ref> He followed this with 88 in a warm up match<ref name=\"ashes06tour\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6165999.stm|title=Cook hits century in warm-up draw|date=10 December 2006|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=20 March 2009}}</ref> but in the following Test he was given out to dubious decisions in both innings, caught for 42 and LBW for a duck, with replays suggesting both decisions were harsh.<ref name=\"aus306\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6185175.stm|title=Awesome Gilchrist savages England|last=Thompson|first=Anna|date=16 December 2006|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=20 March 2009}}</ref> In the Boxing Day Test Strauss secured his only landmark of the series<ref name=\"testanalysis\"/> with an even 50 though he will most likely remembered as [[Shane Warne]]'s 700th Test victim as the Australian spin bowler reached the milestone in his penultimate Test match,<ref name=\"aus406\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6207385.stm|title=Warne landmark as England crumble|last=Soni|first=Paresh|date=26 December 2006|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=20 March 2009}}</ref> by which point the Ashes had been lost.<ref name=\"testanalysis\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/player/20387.html?class=1;template=results;type=allround;view=match|title=Test match analysis|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=20 March 2009}}</ref> As if the five match whitewash was not enough, the final innings of the series for Strauss was marked with a bouncer to the head from [[Brett Lee]] causing him to go to hospital after he was dismissed.<ref name=\"ash506scan\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/275137.html|title=Strauss cleared after scans|date=4 January 2007|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=20 March 2009}}</ref> After the Test series, coach [[Duncan Fletcher]] lamented the lack of confidence in both Strauss and [[Paul Collingwood]] whom he had wished to promote as role models for the rest of the team.<ref name=\"ashsfletch\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6301215.stm|title=Fletcher apologises for big loss|date=27 January 2007|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=20 March 2009}}</ref> Despite the decline in his form towards the end of the year, poor umpiring decisions were taken into account and Strauss was picked as part of the 2006 Wisden Forty.<ref name=\"wis4007\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/287188.html|title=Wisden 2007 \u2013 The Wisden Forty|last=Smyth|first=Lance|author2=Rob Smyth|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=20 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nEngland went from the Test series to a one off Twenty20 International in warm up for the [[Australian Tri-Series|Commonwealth Bank Tri-Series]]. Strauss was omitted from the Twenty20 game but did play for the One Day series. Though England tended to be superior in the long format over the short format, they gained momentum after opening losses and defeated New Zealand in what had become a winner takes all match at the end of the group stages,<ref name=\"nz807tri\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6281543.stm|title=England beat Kiwis to reach final|last=Lillywhite|first=Jamie|date=6 February 2007|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=20 March 2009}}</ref> with Strauss's 55 being the only notable score for him in the series.<ref name=\"odianalysis\"/> By this point Strauss's poor One Day form had been highlighted, with Fletcher admitting he was mostly in the team due to shallow batting options.<ref name=\"norest\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/277562.html|title='We can't rest Strauss' \u2013 Fletcher|date=25 January 2007|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=20 March 2009}}</ref> The half century did nothing for Strauss's confidence though as he fell for a duck in the first final<ref name=\"odianalysis\"/> and only six in the second, though he did take the prized wickets of Ponting and [[Mike Hussey]], restricting them both to single digit scores helping to manipulate the Duckworth-Lewis effected score so that England could win the match without needing the third game.<ref name=\"aus207\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/249241.html|title=2nd Final: Australia v England at Sydney, Feb&nbsp;11 2007|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=20 March 2009}}</ref> His poor form saw him omitted from the group stage of the [[2007 Cricket World Cup|World Cup]] and despite commentators expecting him to make a return for the Super Eights stage against Sri Lanka<ref name=\"cup7un\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/288715.html|title=Uncertain England once again underprepared|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=3 April 2007|publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate=20 March 2009}}</ref> he had to wait to meet old enemies Australia to be recalled, where he only made 7 and had a run-out on Ponting turned down after TV replays.<ref name=\"odianalysis\"/><ref name=\"aus107wc\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/6534575.stm|title=Aussies win despite Pietersen ton|last=Mitchener|first=Mark|date=8 April 2007|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=20 March 2009}}</ref> He batted with England for the rest of the stage until England were knocked out; he would not play One Day cricket for England again until two years later.<ref name=\"odianalysis\"/>\n\nEventually his poor year in both forms of the international form of the game, even after being allowed only to focus on Tests, saw him dropped from the team after 43 Test matches.<ref name=\"tmsprice\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tms/2007/10/strauss_pays_price_for_a_poor.shtml|title=Test match Special: Strauss pays price for a poor year|last=Agnew|first=Jonathan|date=19 October 2007|publisher=BBC  |accessdate=20 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Omission from team and revival in New Zealand====\nStrauss' poor run of form continued through 2007, averaging a low 27 and failing to score a century with a top score of 96.<ref name=rest/> While he continued to play in Test matches against [[India cricket team|India]] and the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], he was dropped from the ODI side. In late 2007, Strauss was not included in the Test squad for the tour of Sri Lanka, and [[Michael Vaughan]] was selected to take his position as opening batsman. Strauss then announced that he was going to take a break from cricket after what he described as a \"long, tiring and immensely frustrating 12 months.\" He was, however, able to travel to India as part of the backup squad if he so wished.<ref name=rest/>\n\nStrauss was thus omitted from England cricket fixtures over the winter. He returned to the Test squad for the tour of New Zealand, however made only four in the first warm up match before hitting his own wicket.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2008/2/14313/html/scorecard.stm ''Tour Match: Invitational XI v England''] [[BBC News]] retrieved 24 February 2008</ref> Despite what was now over 25 Test innings without a century, Strauss was chosen ahead of [[Owais Shah]] (who scored 96 in the same warm up match) to play in the second warm up match, sparking speculation that he would have a place in the Test squad for the first match against New Zealand.<ref name=warm>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7266219.stm ''Warm-up spot boosts Strauss hopes''] [[BBC News]] retrieved 27 February 2008</ref> Strauss was, however, placed in the number three spot on the batting order, leaving Vaughan and Cook to open as they did in [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name=warm/> His batting in the first innings was poor, and he was dismissed for 5. In the second innings, however, he was returned to the position of opener and scored 104* along with Ian Bell.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7272318.stm ''Strauss and Bell find timely form''] [[BBC News]] retrieved 1 March 2008</ref>\n\nStrauss continued to play poorly through the first two matches, and was dismissed for a duck in the first innings of the third. In the second innings, however, he reached a century from 226 deliveries, his slowest but his first since August 2006, going on to make his highest score in Test cricket, 177. This innings seemed to help Strauss re-find his spark as in the first part of the English domestic season that followed he scored runs prolifically for Middlesex, smashing a 163 off 130 balls against Surrey in a domestic one day match.\n\n====New Zealand and South Africa tour England====\nAfter his 177, Strauss's place in the side was guaranteed for the following series against the same opposition. While still ignored for the One Day International team he was given back his position of Test opener alongside Alastair Cook, Michael Vaughan going back down to number 3. In the first rain affected match at Lords he carried on his form with a slow but steady 63 in the only England innings of the match. In the second Test Strauss made another 60 before getting out giving England a decent start following a big first innings total. He then went on to make 106, chasing 294, in the second innings on a now difficult batting wicket which set England up to win by 6 wickets to take a 1\u20130 lead in the three match series. This was Strauss's second Test match century at Old Trafford (the first coming against Australia in 2005, when he also scored 106). In the third and final Test at Trent Bridge he made 37 in England's first and only innings as England went on to win the series 2\u20130. He was named England's man of the series for his 266 runs at an average of 66.50.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/7420284.stm ''Strauss ton inspires England win''] from [[BBC News]] retrieved 26 May 2008</ref>\n\nHis form now impressing the selectors, Strauss was allowed to keep his place for the tour against South Africa. He started on an average note being dismissed for 44 in England's only innings of the first match. He suffered in the second Test at Headlingly, however, making just 27 runs in the first innings and a duck in the second. A pair of 20s resulted as Strauss continued to struggle against the pace bowling of South Africa in the third Test. With England 2\u20130 down going into the last Test, a win was needed to restore pride. Strauss failed in the first innings, being dismissed for six. With the bowlers having got England into a match winning position, Strauss then came good, sharing a century opening stand with Cook and eventually being dismissed for 58. Nevertheless, his place remained under pressure again.\n\n====2008 Tour of India====\nStrauss managed to keep his place for the India tour and immediately rewarded the selectors by making 123 in the first innings of the first Test match with the rest of the batting lagging behind. He followed it up by holding the batting order together after a collapse that saw England 43\u20133 and shared a 200 run partnership with Paul Collingwood in which Strauss and Collingwood both made 108. He became just the 10th Englishman to make two hundreds in the same Test match, with Marcus Trescothick being the last in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/282951.html|title=  Records / Test matches / Batting records / Hundred in each innings of a match |publisher=CricInfo|accessdate=22 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Captaincy====\nStrauss was appointed captain on 7 January 2009 after a rift between previous captain [[Kevin Pietersen]] and Peter Moores became public. Subsequently, Pietersen resigned the captaincy after just 3 Test matches, and Moores was sacked. This came after a rise of form in the 2008 Test Series in India, in which England lost and drew their two games.\n\nIn his first match as regular captain, against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] at [[Sabina Park]], Strauss and his team failed, Strauss scoring 7 and 9 as England were bowled out for 51 in the second innings to lose by an innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/352661.html |title=West Indies v England at Kingston, 2009 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> After the fiasco of the [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/352662.html abandoned Test match], Strauss subsequently had an excellent series with the bat, with scores of 169, 142 and 142 in the remaining three Tests giving him a series aggregate of 541 runs at an average of 67.62,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/20387.html?class=1;series=4326;template=results;type=batting;view=innings |title=Batting records &#124; Test matches &#124; Cricinfo Statsguru &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Stats.cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> but England were unable to force a victory in any of these three matches and consequently lost the series 1\u20130. As captain in the subsequent one-day series, which was drawn 2\u20132, Strauss scored 105 in Guyana<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/352666.html |title=West Indies v England at Guyana, 2009 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> and 79 not out from 61 balls at the [[Kensington Oval]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/352668.html |title=West Indies v England at Bridgetown, 2009 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> He also captained the Twenty20 side to a six-wicket defeat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/england/engine/match/352674.html |title=West Indies v England at Port of Spain, 2009 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> Strauss said to the BBC that he hoped that the whole captaincy debacle would be solved in time for the 2009 Ashes Series.\n\nStrauss atoned for the defeat by the West Indies with a 2\u20130 home victories over the West Indies at home in both the Test and the ODI series. After that series, Strauss had a break from the international circuit while the World Twenty20 was underway. He played two county championship matches to little effect beyond a score of 97 against [[Essex County Cricket Club|Essex]].<ref>Hoult, Nick (22 June 2009). \"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/theashes/5601764/Ashes-2009-England-squad-form-guide.html Ashes 2009: England squad form guide.]\" ''[[The Daily Telegraph|telegraph.co.uk]]''.</ref>\n\n====The Ashes (2009)====\nEngland entered the series hoping to regain the Ashes after a 2007 5\u20130 whitewash.\n\nIn the first Test at [[SWALEC Stadium|Sophia Gardens]], Strauss failed to capitalise on two starts, scoring 30 and 17; his second-innings dismissal, caught off a top-edged cut off [[Nathan Hauritz]], was particularly poor.{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}} On a good batting wicket Australia racked up 674 for 6 declared, with [[Simon Katich]] (122), [[Ricky Ponting]] (150), [[Marcus North]] (125 not out) and [[Brad Haddin]] (121) all scoring centuries. In the second innings, only a dogged 5\u00be-hour 74 from [[Paul Collingwood]] and tail-end contributions salvaged a draw for England, with final pair [[James Anderson (cricketer)|James Anderson]] and [[Monty Panesar]] left to block out the final 11\u00bd overs of the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345970.html |title=England v Australia at Cardiff, 1st Test, 2009 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nEngland entered the second Test at [[Lord's]] having not won an Ashes Test there since [[Hedley Verity]]'s match in the [[Australian cricket team in England in 1934|1934 Ashes]]. On his domestic home ground, Strauss batted through the entire first day of the match for 161 runs, sharing an opening partnership of 196 with [[Alastair Cook]] (95). Though Strauss was bowled by [[Ben Hilfenhaus]]'s second ball the following day without adding to his overnight score, his innings was the highest individual score made by either side during the series, and set up a 210-run first-innings lead. Strauss contributed 32 to England's second innings, as Australia were set a target of 522 to win, a record if achieved. Though Michael Clarke (136), [[Brad Haddin]] (80) and [[Mitchell Johnson (cricketer)|Mitchell Johnson]] (63) briefly made the target seem attainable, [[Andrew Flintoff]] (5\u201392) and [[Graeme Swann]] (4\u201387) bowled England to a comfortable 115-run victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345971.html |title=England v Australia at Lord's, 2nd Test, 2009 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the third Test at [[Edgbaston cricket ground|Edgbaston]], Strauss responded to Australia's first innings of 263 by ending the second day 64 not out; he was removed by [[Ben Hilfenhaus]] the following morning for 69, before England's powerful lower-middle order propelled the side to a 113-run first-innings lead. Australia, however, experienced little difficulty in drawing the match, losing only five wickets in one-and-a-half days thanks to Michael Clarke (103 not out) and [[Marcus North]] (96).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345972.html |title=England v Australia at Birmingham, 3rd Test, 2009 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the fourth Test at [[Headingley Carnegie Cricket Ground|Headingley]], Strauss was distracted before the start of play by team selection issues, with [[Kevin Pietersen]] and [[Andrew Flintoff]] both injured, and a back spasm to [[Matt Prior]] delaying play by ten minutes as his fitness to play was ascertained.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/418290.html |title=Dominant Australia take control |publisher=Cricinfo |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> Strauss' concentration may have been affected by the fire alarm which sounded in the team's hotel at 5&nbsp;am, or by the media interviews he gave immediately before he opened the batting;{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}} he was lucky not to be given out lbw to the first ball of the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/engvaus2009/engine/match/345973.html?innings=1;view=commentary |title=England v Australia at Leeds, 4th Test, 2009: Cricinfo commentary |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> and was removed shortly afterwards for three as England collapsed to 102 all out against [[Peter Siddle]] and [[Stuart Clark]]. More runs for Michael Clarke and [[Marcus North]] led Australia to a total of 445. Strauss and [[Alastair Cook]] responded with an opening partnership of 58 before [[Ben Hilfenhaus]] removed Strauss for 32; England capitulated, this time to Hilfenhaus and Mitchell Johnson en route to an innings defeat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345973.html |title=England v Australia at Leeds, 4th Test, 2009 |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date= |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nEngland therefore entered the fifth Test at [[the Oval]] with the series level at 1\u20131, knowing that only a victory would suffice to bring the Ashes home, as by longstanding convention the Ashes are retained by the current holders in the event of a drawn series. Strauss contributed 55 to England's first innings of 332, before [[Stuart Broad]] (5\u201337) and [[Graeme Swann]] (4\u201338) unexpectedly combined to bowl Australia out for 160. In the second innings Strauss scored 75, sharing a 128-run partnership with debutant [[Jonathan Trott]] (119) to set Australia a target of 546. On the final day of the series, Strauss produced a sharp piece of fielding from leg slip to [[run out]] Michael Clarke for a duck, and also contributed a catch, as Australia were bowled out for 348 to hand England a 197-run victory in the match, a 2\u20131 victory in the series, and the Ashes.\n\nStrauss was named England's man of the series by Australian coach [[Tim Nielsen]]; he finished the series with an aggregate of 474 runs (the highest aggregate by either side; no other England player managed more than 261), at an average of 52.66 (no other England player barring [[Jonathan Trott]], who only played in one match, averaged more than 40). Such was Strauss' dominance with the bat that Australia lost the series despite counting six of the seven leading run-scorers among their number.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/421871.html|title=Strauss's finest hour|date=23 August 2009|website=Cricinfo|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring the following seven-match ODI series, Strauss's contributions led England's batting to the extent that, following the series, [[Andrew Miller (cricket writer)|Andrew Miller]] commented on \"England's guileless middle-order who, for the umpteenth time this summer, treated the loss of Andrew Strauss's wicket with the same grief and disorientation that a clutch of baby chicks might greet the devouring of their mother by a fox.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/current/story/425712.html|title=Swann saves England from whitewash|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=20 September 2009|publisher=CricInfo|accessdate=20 September 2009}}</ref> He spearheaded England's batting efforts with scores of 12, 47, 63, 63, 35, zero and 47 in the series which spanned 4 September until 20 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/20387.html?class=2;template=results;type=batting;view=innings|title=Statistics / Statsguru / AJ Strauss /  One-Day Internationals|publisher=CricInfo|accessdate=20 September 2009}}</ref> He stated on a number of occasions that, despite his own contributions, he was disenchanted by England's poor performances during their 6:1 defeat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/425487.html|title=Strauss laments England's 'horror show'|last=Brown|first=Alex|date=17 September 2009|publisher=CricInfo|accessdate=20 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nYet, for his performances in 2009, he was named in the World Test XI by the ICC <ref> {{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/story/427665.html|title=Johnson and Gambhir scoop top awards|date=2009-10-01|website=Cricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}} </ref>.\n\n====2009\u201310 and 2010====\nFollowing the Ashes, England played in the [[2009 ICC Champions Trophy]]. They beat Sri Lanka and South Africa to unexpectedly reach the semi-finals, however Strauss only managed a top-score of 25. He did not fare much better in the ODI series [[English cricket team in South Africa in 2009\u201310|against South Africa]], which England won 2\u20131. England drew the Test series 1\u20131, however Strauss passed 50 just once.\n\nAfter the tour to South Africa, Strauss was controversially rested for the subsequent [[English cricket team in Bangladesh in 2009\u201310|tour of Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/bdeshveng2010/content/story/444883.html|title=Cook to captain in Bangladesh Tests|publisher=CricInfo.co.uk|date=18 January 2010 }}</ref> In his stead, [[Alastair Cook]] was named captain and [[Michael Carberry]] selected as a replacement opener (though [[Jonathan Trott]] was promoted to opener for the second Test, replacing Carberry). England then won the [[2010 ICC World Twenty20]] in the West Indies under the leadership of Paul Collingwood.\n\nStrauss returned to the Test team in the [[Bangladeshi cricket team in England in 2010|home series against Bangladesh]]. He made two half-centuries as England won the two match series. Between the Tests and the ODI series, England played Australia in a [[Australian cricket team in England in 2010|five match ODI series]] (this was due to Bangladesh's participation in the [[2010 Asia Cup]] during June). England won the series, with Strauss making half-centuries in the second and third games. When Bangladesh returned for the ODI series, Strauss scored a half-century in the first game and a career-best 154 in the third, in which he shared a stand of 250 with [[Jonathan Trott]] who also made a century. England won the three-match series 2\u20131, and Strauss was named Player of the Series. In the accompanying ODI Series Strauss made 126 in the 2nd match of a 5 match series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/8991947.stm|title=Strauss makes 5th Career ODI Century against Pakistan |work=BBC Sport  |date=18 January 2010 | first=Jamie | last=Lillywhite}}</ref>\n\nA [[2010 Pakistan cricket spot-fixing controversy|controversial]] series [[Pakistani cricket team in England in 2010|against Pakistan]] followed. Strauss struggled for form in the Test series, with just one half-century, as England won 3\u20131, bowling Pakistan out for three sub-100 scores. He found form in the five-match ODI series though, with a century and two fifties as England won 3\u20132 in their final series before the [[2010-11 Ashes series]].\n\n====The Ashes (2010\u201311)====\nStrauss headed to the [[2010\u201311 Ashes series]] hoping to join [[Mike Brearley]] and [[Len Hutton]] as the only England captains to win the Ashes both home and away, and the first to win an Ashes series in Australia since [[Mike Gatting]] in 1986-7. \nStrauss won the toss on the opening morning at [[the Gabba]] ([[Brisbane]]) and elected to bat, however was caught at gully for a third-ball duck. England's first innings total of 260 was not enough, and Australia built a 221-run first innings lead. Despite the large deficit, England fought back; Strauss and Cook scored 188 for the first wicket. Strauss made his 19th Test hundred, eventually out for 110; stumped for the first time in his Test career. Fellow-opener Cook scored an unbeaten 235 and [[Jonathan Trott]] 135, also unbeaten, as England declared at 517\u20131. Australia scored 107\u20131 in their second innings before a draw was declared.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2010-11/content/story/489584.html |title=Australia v England, 1st Test, Brisbane, 5th day: England break records in high-scoring draw|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|date=|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the second test match at the Adelaide Oval, Ricky Ponting won the toss and chose to bat but Strauss' bowlers skittled the Aussies for 245, thanks to James Anderson's 4\u201351 . England then made 620\u20135 before declaring but Strauss was out for 1 in that innings. England then bowled Australia out again for 304, with Graeme Swann taking 5\u201391 and England winning by an innings and 71 runs.\n\nIn the third test match at Perth, Strauss won the toss and chose to bowl first. England bowled Australia out for 268 on day one and Strauss scored 12* to guide England to 29\u20130 at stumps. Strauss started well and guided England to 78\u20130 within the first hour of the day's play but a batting collapse saw England bowled out for 187, thanks to Mitchell Johnson's 6\u201338. England struck back and took three Aussie wickets but Australia got to stumps on day two on 119\u20133. Strauss' team then bowled the Aussies out for 309, meaning England required 391 to win but batted poorly to be bowled out for just 123, with Ryan Harris taking 6\u201349 and England losing by 267 runs.\n\nStrauss won the toss at the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]] and elected to bowl on the Boxing Day Test. The decision was an inspired one as England bowled Australia out for 98. In reply, Strauss and Cook had made a 159-run opening stand with Strauss passing 6,000 Test runs before being caught for 69. After England made 513, they bowled Australia out for 258 to win by an innings and 157 runs, therefore retaining the Ashes.\n\nIn the fifth and final Test at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground|SCG]] in Sydney, Strauss lost the toss and [[Michael Clarke (cricketer)|Michael Clarke]], Australian captain in the absence of the injured Ponting, elected to bat. England bowled Australia out for 280. In reply, Strauss made 60 from just 58 balls before being bowled by [[Ben Hilfenhaus]]. England continued to make a score of 644 their highest score on Australian soil, thanks to centuries from [[Alastair Cook]], [[Ian Bell]] and [[Matt Prior]]. Australia fell for 281 in their second innings, handing England a third win by an innings in the series, and an overall 3\u20131 Ashes victory.\n\n====2011 World Cup====\n[[File:Strauss Somerset.jpg|thumb|upright|Strauss batting for Somerset against the touring Indians in July 2011]]\nIn England's opening match of the ICC World cup 2011 against Netherlands, Andrew Strauss hit a better than run-a-ball 88 to get England off to a good start and help them clinch a 6 wicket victory. He maintained this good form the next game, scoring an impressive 158 off 145 chasing an imposing 339 which hosts India had set them. The match ended in a thrilling tie.<ref>{{cite web|last=Amla |first=Hashim |url=http://iccworld-cup2011.blogspot.com/2011/02/england-vs-india-bangalore-27th.html |title=Cricket Matches: England vs India (Bangalore) (27th February) |publisher=Iccworld-cup2011.blogspot.com |date=27 February 2011 |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\nThe third game saw Strauss score 34 off 37 balls as scored 327 against Ireland, but England nonetheless suffered a shock defeat, thanks to a 50-ball 100 by Kevin O'Brien and a 162-run partnership for the 6th wicket.<ref>{{cite web|last=Amla |first=Hashim |url=http://iccworld-cup2011.blogspot.com/2011/03/england-vs-ireland-bangalore-2nd-march.html |title=Cricket Matches: England vs Ireland (Bangalore) (2nd March) |publisher=Iccworld-cup2011.blogspot.com |date=2 March 2011 |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\nEngland then won a thrilling match against South Africa on 6 March, bowling their opponents out for 165 in Chennai to defend a low score of 171, with Stuart Broad claiming 4 vital wickets. The English bowlers derailed the strong Proteas batting lineup, which collapsed from 63 for no loss and lost all their wickets for 102 runs. However, the group stage ended in another shock defeat, this time to Bangladesh, and although England qualified for the quarter-finals, they were comprehensively beaten by Sri Lanka. Strauss duly stepped down from the ODI captaincy and retired from One Day International Cricket.<ref>{{cite web|last=Amla |first=Hashim |url=http://iccworld-cup2011.blogspot.com/2011/03/england-vs-south-africa-chennai-6th.html |title=Cricket Matches: England vs South Africa (Chennai) (6th March) |publisher=Iccworld-cup2011.blogspot.com |date=6 March 2011 |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Retirement====\nStrauss announced his retirement from cricket on 29 August 2012 after 100 test appearances. As a token of appreciation, his teammates bought him 100 bottles of wine, of which he said \"I think that will furnish me nicely into retirement!\" [[Alastair Cook]], his vice-captain and opening partner, was named as his successor. Cook had previously captained England in test matches, as well as being the current ODI captain.<ref>[http://sportsbongo.blogspot.in/2012/08/cricket-andrew-strauss-retires-from-all.html Strauss announces retirement from cricket] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903055415/http://sportsbongo.blogspot.in/2012/08/cricket-andrew-strauss-retires-from-all.html |date=3 September 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Management===\nIn April 2015, a reorganisation at the [[England and Wales Cricket Board|ECB]] saw [[Paul Downton]]'s role of managing director made redundant. Strauss was appointed to the newly created role of director of England cricket in May 2015 and his first act was to sack the incumbent coach [[Peter Moores (cricketer)|Peter Moores]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/872973.html |title=Moores sacked, Strauss made director |publisher=ESPNcricinfo.com |date=9 May 2015| accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref> Another early move was to rule out an imminent return to the England team for Kevin Pietersen, who had fallen out with the previous management team.<ref>{{cite web|title=No Pietersen return \u2013 Strauss|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/874345.html|website=ESPNcricinfo.com|accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref> He oversaw the appointment of [[Trevor Bayliss]] as coach,<ref>{{cite web|title=Bayliss confirmed as England coach|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/881227.html|website=ESPNcricinfo.com}}</ref> and encouraged a greater emphasis to be given to [[limited overs cricket]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrew Strauss: England must focus more on ODIs and T20s|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/34792162|website=BBC}}</ref> Strauss resigned his position on 3 October 2018, citing a wish to spend more time with his wife, Ruth, while she was undergoing treatment for lung cancer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecb.co.uk/news/869444|title=Andrew Strauss steps down as Director of England Cricket|website=Ecb.co.uk|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref> She died on 29 December that year, aged 46.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2018/12/29/andrew-strauss-wife-dies-46-battle-lung-cancer/|title=Andrew Strauss' wife dies at 46 after battle with lung cancer|first=Scyld|last=Berry|date=29 December 2018|accessdate=30 December 2018|website=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Achievements==\n{{see also|List of international cricket centuries by Andrew Strauss}}\n\n===Test cricket===\n[[File:Andrew Strauss test batting career v1.png|center|thumb|750px|An innings-by-innings breakdown of Strauss' Test match batting career, showing runs scored (blue and orange bars) and career batting average (red line). An [[:File:Andrew Strauss test batting career v2.png|image]] showing a 10 innings moving average is also available. Both are current as at 14 January 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://stats.espncricinfo.com/stats/engine/player/20387.html?class=1;template=results;type=batting;view=innings|author = [[ESPNcricinfo]]|accessdate =14 January 2012|publisher = [[ESPN]]|title =Statistics / Statsguru / AJ Strauss / Test matches}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.howstat.com.au/cricket/Statistics/Players/PlayerProgressBat.asp?PlayerID=3148|title = Andrew J Strauss \u2013 Test Cricket|accessdate =14 January 2012|publisher = Howstat Computing Services}}</ref>]]\n\n====Test records against each opponent====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"  style=\"font-size:95%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! Opponent !! Matches !! Innings !! Not out !! Runs !! Balls !! High Score !! 100 !! 50 !! Average !! Strike Rate\n|-\n| {{cr|AUS}} || 20 || 36 || 0 || 1,421 || 2,809 || 161 || 4 || 7 || 39.47 || 50.58\n|-\n| {{cr|BAN}} || 4 || 5 || 0 || 263 || 385 || 83 || 0 || 3 || 52.60 || 68.31\n|-\n| {{cr|IND}} || 12 || 22 || 1 || 929 || 2,180 || 128 || 3 || 3 || 44.23 || 42.61\n|-\n| {{cr|NZ}} || 9 || 16 || 0 || 813 || 1,728 || 177 || 3 || 4 || 50.81 || 47.04\n|-\n| {{cr|PAK}} || 13 || 24 || 1 || 793 || 1,548 || 128 || 2 || 3 || 34.47 || 51.22\n|-\n| {{cr|RSA}} || 16 || 30 || 1 || 1,113 || 2,361 || 147 || 3 || 3 || 38.37 || 47.14\n|-\n| {{cr|SRI}} || 8 || 13 || 0 || 297 || 644 || 55 || 0 || 2 || 22.84 || 46.11\n|-\n| {{cr|WIN}} || 18 || 32 || 3 || 1,408 || 2,730 || 169 || 6 || 2 || 48.55 || 51.57\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| '''TOTAL''' || 100 || 178 || 6 || 7,037 || 14,385 || 177 || 21 || 27 || 40.91 || 48.91\n|}\n\nAbove data from [[ESPNcricinfo]] and current as at 25 December 2015.<ref name = \"Cricinfo career summary\" />\n\n====Test analysis by year====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Matches !! Innings !! Not Out !! Runs !! High Score !! Average !! Strike Rate !! 100 !! 50\n|-\n| 2004 || 9 || 18 || 2 || 971 || 137 || 60.68 || 50.89 || 4 || 4\n|-\n| 2005 || 12 || 22 || 0 || 789 || 147 || 35.86 || 52.18 || 3 || 1\n|-\n| 2006 || 14 || 26 || 0 || 1,031 || 128 || 39.65 || 49.95 || 3 || 3\n|-\n| 2007 || 8 || 15 || 0 || 432 || 96 || 28.80 || 47.21 || 0 || 3\n|-\n| 2008 || 12 || 21 || 1 || 972 || 177 || 48.60 || 43.54 || 4 || 3\n|-\n| 2